Are consumers too deep in hock?@#%^&*1
A lot of observers think so,@#%^&*1
and,@#%^&*1
if they're right,@#%^&*1
the whole economy as well as the spendthrifts among us could be hurt.@#%^&*1
A sudden, forced cutback by consumers,@#%^&*2
who normally account for about two-thirds of economic activity,@#%^&*2
would damp the economy at a time@#%^&*2
when plant-and-equipment spending is slowing@#%^&*2
and deficit-racked governments can't readily take up the slack.@#%^&*2
And another wave of bad loans would further batter many already-shaky lending institutions.@#%^&*3
The worriers cite some worrisome trends.@#%^&*4
During the almost seven-year-old economic expansion, inflation-adjusted gross national product, disposable personal income and personal consumption expenditures have risen 30%,@#%^&*5
but inflation-adjusted consumer installment credit has surged 66%.@#%^&*5
And the ratio of installment debt to disposable personal income@#%^&*6
-- personal income after taxes --@#%^&*6
has hit a high of about 18 1/2%.@#%^&*6
However, these figures don't seem to worry Thomas A. Durkin, an economist at the Federal Reserve Board.@#%^&*7
In a paper@#%^&*8
presented at the recent annual meeting of the National Association of Business Economists in San Francisco,@#%^&*8
Mr. Durkin comments@#%^&*8
that "installment credit always grows rapidly in cyclical advances,@#%^&*8
and growth in this cycle is very typical of earlier experiences."@#%^&*8
He adds:@#%^&*9
"We are now witnessing a slowdown@#%^&*9
which,@#%^&*9
if history is a guide,@#%^&*9
could persist for a while."@#%^&*9
But what about the debt burden?@#%^&*10
Mr. Durkin doubts@#%^&*10
that "there is some magic level"@#%^&*10
at which the ratio of installment debt to disposable income "indicates economic problems."@#%^&*10
And, "more importantly,"@#%^&*11
he says,@#%^&*11
"the debt burden@#%^&*11
measured other ways@#%^&*11
is not really in uncharted waters."@#%^&*11
The chart below shows why@#%^&*12
