The ratio of consumer installment credit to disposable income, though up a bit, hasn't climbed steeply,@#%^&*13
and such debt as a percent of household assets is little changed.@#%^&*13
Moreover, the burden of consumer credit payments relative to disposable income may be "lower in this cycle than earlier,"@#%^&*14
Mr. Durkin says.@#%^&*14
He notes@#%^&*15
that some "revolving credit-card credit is actually convenience credit"@#%^&*15
being used simply as a handy way@#%^&*15
of paying bills@#%^&*15
rather than a handy way@#%^&*15
of borrowing.@#%^&*15
In addition, he says,@#%^&*16
"longer maturities on automobile and other forms of installment credit boost the stock of debt faster than the flow of repayments and the accompanying payment burden."@#%^&*16
And@#%^&*17
if you "consider the changing distribution of credit,"@#%^&*17
Mr. Durkin says,@#%^&*17
"much of the increase in debt in recent years is due to increasing credit use by higher-income families,"@#%^&*17
that is, "those probably best able to handle it."@#%^&*17
Citing figures on home-equity loans,@#%^&*18
he notes@#%^&*18
that "11% of homeowners had home-equity credit accounts,@#%^&*18
but the proportion rises to 16% of homeowners in the $45,000-$60,000 income range and 23% of homeowners with income above $60,000."@#%^&*18
And much home-equity credit is used conservatively.@#%^&*19
"The most frequent use is home improvement,@#%^&*20
which presumably improves the value of the property,"@#%^&*20
Mr. Durkin says.@#%^&*20
So, it isn't surprising that consumer-credit delinquencies at banks remain,@#%^&*21
