A severe recession could, of course, raise delinquency rates,@#%^&*22
but so far the current levels of consumer debt don't seem to loom as a major threat.@#%^&*22
In fact, the current weakness in auto buying and department-store sales and the gradual upturn in the household saving rate suggest@#%^&*23
that consumers, conservative as ever, are already clutching their purses a bit more tightly.@#%^&*23
In July, consumer installment credit outstanding fell for the first time since January 1987.@#%^&*24
"Consumers appear unwilling to add to their leverage@#%^&*25
to support their spending,"@#%^&*25
Bruce Steinberg, a Merrill Lynch economist, says.@#%^&*25
"As a result, household debt appears to be stabilizing at around 63% of GNP."@#%^&*26
